{
  "doc_id": "57074",
  "text": "DNA samples were obtained from blood specimens or cultured cells by phenol-chloroform extraction and ethanol precipitation. Markers analyzed include 77 biallelic polymorphisms ( fig. 1 ) and seven STRs (four di-and three tetranucleotide repeats). The majority of the biallelic markers were genotyped according to a hierarchical approach, on the basis of the phylogeny reported by [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Using this approach, we were able to assign all of the African chromosomes to 37 specific haplotypes of the 131 haplotypes reported by [CITATION_3] , with the caveat that, when a terminal branch of the tree proposed by [CITATION_4] was more than one mutation long, only a subset of the markers on that branch was typed in the present study.",
